[normal]Written evidence from [bold]West Sussex Cycle Forum[bold] (LTD0003)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In the guidance for those submitting evidence - it is 
[normal]advised to b
[normal]egin with a short summary in bullet point form
[normal].   I think that our responses 
[normal]to the points you raise are short and to the point, and speak for themselves.   However, here is a short summary in bullet point format.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question number
[normal]Question posed by 
[normal]The Transport 
[normal]Committee
[normal]Answers submitted by the West Sussex Cycle Forum
[normal]1
[normal]What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s 
[normal]approach? Are there better models?
[normal]There are a number of disadvantages 
[normal]associated with
[normal] devolved decision-making in West Sussex:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Expectations
[normal] have been raised that local decision-making would direct money more effectively to the needs of cyclists, but as the rest of this response demonstrates, the 
[normal]implementation in West Sussex has largely dashed those expectations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolving transport decision
[normal]s makes it almost impossible to plan and deliver non-local transport infrastructure, even on the scale of inter-urban 
[normal]cycleways
[normal] between 
[normal]neighbouring
[normal] towns [
[normal]see 
[normal]1].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Transport is by its nature a very network-oriented issue, so changes in one location can ha
[normal]ve big impacts on another location: but 
[normal]localised
[normal] transport spending doesn't allow this to be taken into account at all [
[normal]see 
[normal]2]. Transport-specific planning and design knowledge is lost, as local councils do not have the expertise and experience in transpo
[normal]rt planning matters [
[normal]see 
[normal]3].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Examples - 
[normal][1] A county 
[normal]councillor
[normal] from Lancing would like to build a 
[normal]cycleway
[normal] between Lancing and 
[normal]Worthing
[normal], to benefit Lancing residents. However most of the 
[normal]cycleway
[normal] will be within 
[normal]Worthing's
[normal] boundary, so he has to persuade 
[normal]a 
[normal]Worthing
[normal] 
[normal]councillor
[normal] to promote his 
[normal]cycleway
[normal], even though it has much less value to 
[normal]Worthing
[normal] residents. This means that it's unlikely to ever happen; even though there is local community need and desire.
[normal]&gt; [2] The A27 through 
[normal]Worthing
[normal] is likely to become 
[normal]significantly more congested when the improvements at 
[normal]Handcross
[normal] Hill on the A23 are completed, making it much easier to drive to the south coast from Gatwick and further north. If the Arundel bypass 
[normal]were ever to be
[normal] built, 
[normal]it
[normal] would lead to significant incre
[normal]ases in congestion in 
[normal]Worthing
[normal] from traffic finding it easier to drive along the A27 to and from the west. The A27 at Southampton is significantly more congested since the M3 
[normal]Twyford
[normal] Down cutting opened.
[normal]&gt; [3] Local officials recently placed a sharp-edged 
[normal]dark-blue sculpture in the middle of National Cycle Network Route 2 
[normal]cycleway
[normal] in Lancing. The local officers involved were unaware of the importance of this route, or the number of people on bicycles using it daily to commute to and from work. One officer w
[normal]as even unaware that the cycle route was continuous to 
[normal]Worthing
[normal], even though it had been so for some years!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]·
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport 
[normal]authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?
[normal]I take local to mean exactly that - within a locality such as a town or borough, or a disti
[normal]nct and separate rural area.   The great weakness of the current system is that local government at the County level has been subjected to cutbacks and seemingly constant 
[normal]rationalisations
[normal] (i.e. redundancies and 
[normal]reorganisations
[normal]).   This has created disconti
[normal]nuity and a certain amount of corporate paralysis.   There seems to be no overarching coherent policy that requires urgency to deliver it.   For example - there is evidence that S106 money is held up by bureaucracy.   There are no longer budgets allocated 
[normal]to specific means of transport which means that - for example, cycle schemes that might deliver real benefit don't get 
[normal]recognised
[normal] as part of a core transport policy - more as a fringe and 
[normal]marginalised
[normal] form of transport; although the talk in public is diffe
[normal]rent.   The CLC process is incapable of dealing with the volume that should go through its hands.   Consequently, those schemes that are easy to understand and 
[normal]quickly 
[normal]decide on - get the vote.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Apart from benefitting from some isolated serendipitous schem
[normal]es, West Sussex County Council has not made any serious attempt to implement its 
[normal]Local Plan Transport Plan 3
[normal] (LTP3) 
[normal]and has, similarly, made no attempt to replace it with anything else.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This, therefore, poses the question ‘what is the point of all of the 
[normal]effort put in to these plans if the Council has no mechanism to support it or implementing it?’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To answer the question - 
[normal]local bodies do not have the capacity to assess, 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] and deliver local transport schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The optimum delivery body is one th
[normal]at considers and values the economic, health and 
[normal]social benefits of sustainable transport, and incorporates those benefits into an integrated policy with a 'golden thread' running through transport, health, social and economic development policies.   It sh
[normal]ould consult with, and take 'on the ground' information from, those who know the locality.   Those consulted should be involved in the roll out of schemes.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Local bodies (district and borough councils) are inconsistent in their approach to sustainable tr
[normal]ansport. Decisions made by the county council in allocating funding to sustainable transport are not backed-up by, and are even contradicted by, decisions of Council Local Committees. The co-ordination of cycle schemes at county council level has been aban
[normal]doned with the abolition of the West Sussex County Council Cycling Officer and although there is someone doing his best to work with local cycle and sustainable transport groups, the fact is that he has another full time job that takes all his time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]·
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?
[normal]Have a scheme-by-scheme project led team that is charged with delivering on time and on budget and takes in all 
[normal]economic, health and social benefits of sustainable transport.  Its members are the stakeholders in the geographical area as well as those intimately involved with the various modes of transport being considered.
